<center><font size=10>'''''Sometimes, in our pursuit of our desires, we fail to realize that expectations never completely line up with reality...'''''</font></center>








<center><font size=10>'''''...and if something feels too good to be true, then it almost always is.'''''</font></center>









<div style="background-color:#000000; color: white; margin:1em; padding:5px 10px; border:2px solid #FFFFFF; border-radius: 3px">
<br>
<br>
<br>

{{Collapse|num=1|initial=<span style="color:#FFAAF3; text-shadow: 0 0 5px gold; font-size: 24px"><center>[[File:Screenshot 2025-04-26 192345-NEW Level 434-1.png|link=|center|700x700px]]</center></span>|final=<span style="color:#FF23E1; text-shadow: 0 0 30px #08D5E1; font-size: 30px"><center>{{Image Banner|image=Screenshot 2025-04-26 192345-NEW Level 434-1.png}}</center></span>|body=

<div style="color:#FFFFFF; text-shadow: 0 0 30px magenta; font-size: 20px"><center>
I looked around. The unending housing blocks stretched for miles, portrayed in many different colors, styles, and shapes. Some were as small as a typical trailer, while others grew to the size of mansions. The cloudless sky emitted a static shade of blue. A body of light loomed within the sky, casting a constant stream of light. The ground below me was covered in large patches of grass, which emitted an everlasting shade of green. There was no one around me, despite the promises of community. In fact, all semblance of life was taken away. No happiness, no joy, no celebration. Sounds were nonexistent, with no chirp, no wind, nothing but my footsteps echoing on the asphalt roads winding through the neighborhood. 

Though the nature of my surroundings were telling me to relax and put my guard down, I could not bear myself to do so. Everything carried an overwhelming sameness, no matter the exterior appearances of each structure. An artificial air surrounded me, as if this "community" was constructed to be a twisted portrayal of one designed to control others. I picked up an advertisement flyer laying on the ground, detailing everything this place had to offer. Each image contained depictions of picturesque surroundings and self-portraits of large families and individual people, all with a smile on their face. However, these smiles felt off and unnatural. Some were too big, others too small, and others more simply carrying an uneasy feeling.

At the bottom of the flyer, I saw the words that would be emblazoned into my head forever: "Come to Yonder, perfect life, perfect families, forever".
</center></div>
{{Collapse|num=2|initial=<span style="color:#FFAAF3; text-shadow: 0 0 5px gold; font-size: 24px"><center>[[File:Screenshot 2025-04-04 082038-434-2-1.png|link=|center|700x700px]]</center></span>|final=<span style="color:#FF23E1; text-shadow: 0 0 30px #08D5E1; font-size: 30px"><center>{{Image Banner|image=Screenshot 2025-04-04 082038-434-2-1.png}}</center></span>|body=

<div style="color:#FFFFFF; text-shadow: 0 0 30px #0877CC; font-size: 20px"><center>
As I explored the abodes that made up the defining feature of the level, I noticed that each was similar, same layout, same style, and same characteristics. The coffee pot in the kitchen was in the same position each time, the flowerpots in the living room contained the same flowers, and the mirror on the bathroom wall always hung above the sink, to the right of the showers, and was consistently circular in design. The only differences were the wallpaper in the smaller bedroom, which was either painted blue or pink, seemingly for either a boy or a girl.

Though outward appearances suggested the opposite, the bed and couches did not feel comfortable and were stiff as a regular deck chair. The only consumables I was able to find was a cereal box and a carton of milk, both sporting a large logo stating “PASSION FARMS”. Since I was hard pressed for food, I opened the box, put it up to my mouth, and dumped a number of flakes into it. Immediately, I noticed that the food was tasteless and bland. The milk yielded the same effect, though both managed to fill me enough to continue on.

A number of paintings lined the walls of each household, and just like every other attribute, these paintings were all starkly similar. Most of them showed the outside of a particular house within the neighborhood; a distinct blue colored one, although there would always be two that stood out, with one showing a supposed bird's eye of the development with the sun setting off into the distance and the "Yonder" logo in the corner. The other one showed a smiling couple, as realistic as a photograph. This painting carried the same air of the photos within the advertisement flyer: uncanny smiles. Unlike the advertisement photos, which at least had toothy grins, these smiles were completely black and curved unnaturally upwards. No eyes were present of both of their faces. At the bottom were words written similar to an artist's signature in black ink, though when I looked closer, I read the true words: "You never have to worry about home again!"
</center></div>

{{Collapse|num=3|initial=<span style="color:#FFAAF3; text-shadow: 0 0 5px gold; font-size: 24px"><center>[[File:Screenshot 2025-04-04 082056-434-1-3.png|link=|center|700x700px]]</center></span>|final=<span style="color:#FF23E1; text-shadow: 0 0 30px #08D5E1; font-size: 30px"><center>{{Image Banner|image=Screenshot 2025-04-04 082056-434-1-3.png}}</center></span>|body=

<div style="color:#FFFFFF; text-shadow: 0 0 30px #008000; font-size: 20px"><center>
As I continually wandered the level, I noticed myself slowly becoming hollow, as if the level was slowly mending me with its lifeless nature, and sucking me dry, bit by bit. As I walked, I noticed my movements gradually become erratic, similar to a wounded animal. Emotional responses became dull, with a robotic conscience replacing it. I no longer felt an overwhelming uncanny feeling, nor any desire to escape. Physical feeling was slowly leaving me as well. I no longer felt my legs walking, the weight of the backpack on my shoulders, or the light in my eyes. I felt like I was a walking doll, but alive and made of organs. Physical pain became nonexistent, in fact, as I accidentally tripped and skidded on the concrete sidewalk, I felt no pain, despite the ever-present bruise on my left knee.

Shortly afterwards, I noticed a humanoid figure wearing a green sweatshirt, khaki shorts and a pair of yellow sneakers. As soon as I saw him, I immediately began to run to him. "Another wanderer" I thought. But as I approached, I noticed something odd, he shared a sullen robotic movement, and barely even acknowledged me when I came close. It was only after I called out to him that he stopped short. After a second long delay, he began to turn towards me, revealing his face, but it was far from human. He had no eyes with only dull sockets in its place. He had a static smile, which was locked in the same position. His smile had an uncanny similarity to the painting at the houses I entered earlier, with the same unnatural curve, and the same vantablack appearance, with no teeth whatsoever.

Usually, I would have pulled out my trusty firearm and shot him in the face. But instead, I just observed with a mix of fear and awe. My legs became stone as I was frozen in place. After a long silent pause, he looked at me, and spoke with a solemn tone to his voice: "Greetings, you must be a new neighbor, as you are not hollow yet. Welcome to the quaint suburban community known as Yonder. You look like you are lost, let me show you around." As he spoke, his voice sounded like one of a robot, cold and calculated.

At that moment, I turned around to run, the last ounce of fear left in me pushing me on. As I ran, I noticed that I no longer felt my own legs. His words kept replaying in my mind as I kept running: "You must be a new neighbor, as you are not hollow yet." I continually dwelled on these words, and my fear turned to dread. Is this what I was destined to become? Is my desire for adventure and discovery going to be my end as a human?

</center></div>

{{Collapse|num=4|initial=<span style="color:#FFAAF3; text-shadow: 0 0 5px gold; font-size: 24px"><center>[[File:Screenshot 2025-04-19 142522-Level 434-6.png|link=|center|700x700px]]</center></span>|final=<span style="color:#FF23E1; text-shadow: 0 0 30px #08D5E1; font-size: 30px"><center>{{Image Banner|image=Screenshot 2025-04-19 142522-Level 434-6.png}}</center></span>|body=

<div style="color:#FFFFFF; text-shadow: 0 0 30px #f5c71a; font-size: 20px"><center>
Nightfall hit me like a ton of bricks. At first, I noticed the change in the lighting all around me, and then I noticed the "sun" moving towards the western direction. Sunset only took 5 minutes, after that everything was cast into darkness. A duller light, resembling the Moon, rose as soon as the "sun" sank below the ground, and the whole level was cast into complete darkness for a brief moment. Afterwards, streetlights began to turn on, illuminating the street ahead of me. The houses all around me turned on their lights in sequential order, never skipping a second. The new change brought a bit of life into the entire level, yet it all felt false, as if it was all meant to keep one at ease, so that they would never expect anything to happen.

The numbness and hollowness spread to my whole body, and by this point I did not feel anything, not even my own breath. As nighttime passed, something else began to change within the houses around me, silhouettes of people reflected in the lit-up windows of each dwelling. Whole families, couples, and individuals hanging out in the comfort of the light. At first, they seemed to be partaking in normal activities, such as watching TV, playing board games, and cooking meals within the kitchen.

However, things began to take a turn as the night progressed. Each silhouette stopped their activities, one by one, and turned towards their window, before entering into a stasis; unmoving. Moving deeper into the level brought more changes. Each shadow was frozen in unnatural positions, such as on the ground, stuck in an upright formation on the ceiling, and other contortions. Even though some part of me figured that the shadows were just an illusion created by the level, and that actually entering would reveal an unoccupied house, I never went in myself to see.

As I walked alongside a side street with few houses on it, I suddenly felt a large pain within my head, pounding like a knock on a steel door. The migraine quickly got worse, and soon enough, I was hunched over on the sidewalk, holding my head and wincing as if I had suffered a big fall. I relented from holding my head to look up and saw the housing developments continuing on forever. At that moment, I started reflecting on my life choices, my experiences within the Backrooms, and that one motivation that brought me here, to explore and document a new level.

Then everything went black.
</center></div>

{{Collapse|num=5|initial=<span style="color:#FFAAF3; text-shadow: 0 0 5px gold; font-size: 24px"><center>[[File:Screenshot 2025-04-24 130235-434-7.png|link=|center|700x700px]]</center></span>|final=<span style="color:#FF23E1; text-shadow: 0 0 30px #08D5E1; font-size: 30px"><center>{{Image Banner|image=Screenshot 2025-04-24 130235-434-7.png}}</center></span>|body=

<div style="color:#FFFFFF; text-shadow: 0 0 30px #ff8c00; font-size: 20px"><center>
The mirror hung on the bathroom wall, like always. I found myself staring into it, my reflection doing the same. The sink was turned on, continually emitting a singular stream of water from the faucet, into the drain. I barely remembered anything of the night prior, other than the endless suburban expanse illuminated by streetlights. I put my hand in the path of the sink, no feeling of water, despite the water being the coldest it could get. I turned the tab the other way. Soon enough, a large plume of steam began flowing from the sink, and condensation followed. I stick my hand in again. Nothing, no burns, no sensation of heat.

I have become completely hollow.

Pondering over this facet, my old instincts began to return. I realized that I needed to escape, as I had no idea what this place was doing to me. I knew that I would probably never regain my old senses of pain and feelings, that I would probably remain hollow forever. But I was probably not too late to exit, and the hollowness will still go away once I left the level. Even if it won’t, being hollow had its benefits. I would be immune to any pain or injuries, be able to walk on a broken foot long enough to seek medical attention. As well as that, if I ever got attacked by an entity, my death would not be as painful as normal.

As I prepare to leave the bathroom, another headache hits me, same exact place, same exact intensity. The last thing I saw was the mirror I was once staring at with optimism, and then everything went black yet again.
</center></div>

{{Collapse|num=6|initial=<span style="color:#FFAAF3; text-shadow: 0 0 5px gold; font-size: 24px"><center>[[File:Level 434-8.png|link=|center|700x700px]]</center></span>|final=<span style="color:#FF23E1; text-shadow: 0 0 30px #08D5E1; font-size: 30px"><center>{{Image Banner|image=Level 434-8.png}}</center></span>|body=

<div style="color:#FFFFFF; text-shadow: 0 0 30px #ff0000; font-size: 20px"><center>
As I came to, I found myself laying on a couch within the living room of a house. Looking out the window in front of me, I saw that it was an early evening, with sunset preparing to take place. I got up from the couch and wandered out of the living room, into the foyer, ready to leave the house, and the level entirely.

Thats when I noticed the pictures hanging on the foyer's wall.

All of them have changed. Instead of the typical pictures of the level, or pictures of specific houses within the neighborhood, they were all replaced with the same photorealistic pictures of individuals smiling, with the same vantablack grins and eyes as the paintings I encountered firstly upon entering and the man who I met wandering the streets. However, this time, instead of looking at them with fear, something told me to admire them, as if they were the depictions of a perfect life. I saw them with dogs, smiling and playful as ever. I saw them with milkshakes, with the PASSION FARMS brand emblazoned across the whole cup. I saw them in cars, driving around, enjoying the sunset.

While I admired the paintings, thoughts about my own predicament within this level began to flow within my mind. Why was I even trying to escape in the first place? Back to some desolate and miserable realm where I was capable of meeting a painful death at the hands of a monster? Was life here really that bad? This place did not have any environmental hazards that I was aware of, and every ounce of food I took was instantly replenished by the next second. At any moment during the day, I could go outside and walk. Even though there were drawbacks to living here, the chances of finding a level that had this number of perks was almost zero to none.

And so, I made the decision to make this level my new home forever. I went outside and admired the sunset. I thought about what my new life would look like in a place like this, what raising a family would be like. As the sun began to sink below the horizon, I smiled to myself, knowing that the future was finally bright, and that I have finally found a safe haven to live in.

There were, of course, contradicting thoughts, but they would be all repelled by one single statement:

<font size=5>"Silly neighbor, you are home!"</font>

</center></div>
